# AW Analysis — Cursor rules

## Project
Cross-asset market intelligence agent. Python 3.11+, src/ layout, package name `aw_analysis`.

## Code style
- British English in comments and docstrings.
- Type hints required on public functions.
- `from __future__ import annotations` at the top of every module.
- Imports: stdlib, third-party, local — separated by blank lines.

## Architecture
- `client/` wraps the Anthropic SDK. Agent code never imports `anthropic` directly.
- `data_sources/` are plain HTTP clients. They know nothing about the agent.
- `tools/` wrap data sources with Anthropic-facing schemas and descriptions.
- `agent/` orchestrates the message loop and tool dispatch.
- `prompts/` hold system prompts as Python constants.

## When editing
- Tool descriptions are load-bearing. Be specific about when to use a tool.
- Errors inside tools should be returned as strings, not raised, so the agent loop survives.
- New tools get registered in `cli/main.py`'s `_build_registry`.

## Stage 5 conventions:
- Every model call goes through AnthropicClient.create with an explicit
  ModelConfig. Never pass model/temperature/max_tokens as bare kwargs.
- Use TaskType enum values, not magic strings.
- Token counts come from client.count_tokens(), never from len(text)/4.
- New per-task settings go in MODEL_CONFIG_REGISTRY in
  aw_analysis/config/model_config.py with a populated rationale field.


## Stage 6 conventions (Evaluation & Testing)
- The eval harness lives in `evals/`, a sibling of `aw_analysis/`.
  `evals/` imports from `aw_analysis`. `aw_analysis/` MUST NEVER import
  from `evals/`. Production code does not depend on the eval harness.
- Every Assertion has an explicit AssertionKind. Adding a new kind
  requires (a) a new enum value, (b) a new handler in
  evals/grader/deterministic.py, (c) a new entry in _HANDLERS.
- The judge uses TaskType.JUDGE via get_model_config. Never instantiate
  a model call inside evals/grader/judge.py with a different config.
- The judge's rubric is versioned as a constant (JUDGE_RUBRIC_VERSION).
  Changing rubric wording requires bumping the version and re-running
  calibration. Stale calibration reports are not reused.
- Every EvalCase has a `rationale` field that is at least one sentence.
  A case without a rationale is a vibe; refuse to write one.
- When proposing changes to the eval runner's _adjudicate function, do
  not collapse the deterministic and judge layers into one score. They
  must remain reportable independently. Disagreement is signal.
- British English in comments, docstrings, and prose throughout.

## Stage 8 conventions (observability)

- Every model call's trace data is also a Langfuse observation.
  The emit layer lives in `aw_analysis/obs/`; every call site
  goes through `aw_analysis.obs.emitter`.  No other module
  imports `langfuse` directly.

- Observability is soft-required.  If `LANGFUSE_PUBLIC_KEY` is
  unset, the emitter is a no-op AND prints exactly one warning
  to stderr on first call.  Silent no-op is forbidden.

- Attribute names are constants in `aw_analysis/obs/attributes.py`.
  Do not introduce ad-hoc string keys for metadata.  When a new
  attribute is needed, add it to attributes.py first, then
  reference the constant at the emit site.

- Emit functions MUST NEVER raise.  Wrap any failure in a broad
  except and silently absorb (the Langfuse SDK has its own debug
  logging).  An observability bug must never bring down the agent.

- Generation observations are for LLM calls only.  Tool calls are
  spans.  The classifier call is a generation inside a span named
  `decomposer.classify`.  Do not collapse these.

- Tags are for top-level UI filtering: `prompt:<version>`,
  `interface:cli|eval`, `run:<run_id>`.  Per-observation slicing
  goes in metadata, not tags.

- The framework adoption stance: Langfuse is the ONE adopted
  framework.  Do not propose LangChain, LangGraph, Pydantic AI,
  or LiteLLM refactors.  If a problem cannot be solved without
  one of those, raise it in chat before writing code.